1.        HR OVERSIGHT APPLICATION - GENERAL META DATA

 

A.       Description:

 

In terms of the Public Service Regulations, 2001 (Chapter 1, Part III, Section J), specific statistics and information need to be included in the annual report. The Minister of the Department of Public Service and Administration (DPSA) has prescribed this requirement for all government departments within the Public Service. Annual reports are then produced after the end of the financial year.

 

The Vulindlela HR Oversight Reporting System was developed and implemented in 2002 to assist in producing these annual reports. The system was rolled-out and a few enhancements were required to the application as well as to the HR Oversight format. These new requirements to the HR Oversight format were applied by the DPSA and a new format was published. 

 

A new application was developed from the newly published format, which also includes the enhancements identified in the previous application. This new reporting tool serves the purpose of assisting the users in compiling their annual reports. As the data available on the PERSAL source system is not always a true reflection of the current status within some departments, users will be allowed to modify current figures and capture new values where required. This will be achieved by downloading the reports in an Excel format from the Web, which have been populated with the data as extracted form the source system. This will allow capturing and modifications to the current available data.

 

The Vulindlela HR Oversight Reporting system aims to equip and empower all the role-players in meeting the corresponding requirements of annual reporting as prescribed by the Public Service Regulations, 2001 (Chapter 1, Part III, Section J). This will be done by providing the facility to report on current figures, as it is currently stored on the source system, as well as giving the role-players the opportunity to capture additional figures and to modify current figures in an Excel spreadsheet.

 

Reports from the system must achieve balance between presenting sufficient detail to be meaningful without overburdening the preparer or swamping the reader; focusing on critical outputs with accurate and timely date, presented attractively and concisely.

This project will be developed in two phases. The requirements as specified in the HR Oversight Business Requirements document will only be for the first phase of the project.  Refer to the Recommendations (Section 5.5 of above document) for detail on the second phase.

B.       Definition:

 

HR Oversight provides for the facilitation of annual reports, in compliance with the requirements of the Public Service Regulations in terms of the following: Service Delivery; Expenditure; Employment and Vacancies; Job Evaluation; Employment Changes; Employment Equity; Performance Rewards; Foreign Workers; Leave Utilisation; HIV/AIDS & Health Promotion Programmes; Labour Relations; Skills Development; Injury on Duty; Utilisation of Consultants.

 

The above will be undertaken for both National- and Provincial departments. The end-product will be made user-friendly to both the report capturers and readers and will add value by offering the convenience of

·          remote access (via the web)

·          pre-population of the relevant actual values, as recorded on the source system.

 

According to the Public Service Regulations there are prescribed formats for these annual reports that are produced after the end of the financial year. The statistical tables provide high-level information on key human resource, financial and service delivery issues. The information aims to empower legislatures, the media, the public and other key stakeholders to monitor whether departments:

·          Exercise the powers granted under Public Service and Public Finance legislation in a responsible manner;

·          Achieve the plans that it set for itself in the Estimate of National Expenditure;

·          Achieve national transformation priorities established by the Cabinet, for example, Affirmative Action.

C.       General Business Rules:

 

Reports are provided in the format as prescribed by the Public Service Regulations, 2001 (Chapter 1, Part III, Section J). Formatting of the reports by the users should therefore also be done in the desired format as prescribed for the annual report.

 

All data is extracted from the PERSAL source system to populate the reports. 

 

No history prior to 1 April 2003 are kept or loaded into the application. All new/current records are kept  nothing is overwritten. Records from new extractions from the source system should only be added to existing records. History will be built from this stage/date onward.

 

Allowance is made for the capturing of additional information required by the PSR for annual reporting that is not captured on the source system, as well as for the modification of figures as extracted from the source system by providing populated as well as blank reports.

 

Summary tables are provided in the following hierarchy:

·          RSA

·          National/Province

·          Cluster/Sector

·          Department.

 

Dates in the heading of all the reports/tables should be as follows:

Heading as on Oversight Report

Heading as on Application

2003/2004

For the reporting period

31 March 2004

As at the end of reporting period

1 April 2003 to 31 March 2004

For the reporting period

1 April 2003

As at the start of the reporting period

 

Number of employees is the number of employees on the PERSAL System, i.e. employees in the Public Service at a specific time. Duplicate PERSAL numbers will only count as one employee.

 

All reports with a reference to posts show a split between temporary and permanent posts. Only active approved posts are counted. 

 

The following Post Status codes are used to indicate temporary posts:

04: Temporary

05: Contract

08: Casual Labour, M

09: Casual Labour, D

10: Casual Labour, H

19: Services, temporary

26: CS Educator, temporary

28: CS Educator, relieve

30: Education Specialist, temporary

34: Part time Teacher

 

The following Post Status codes are used to indicate permanent posts (approved Establishment):

1: Active, filled

2: Lent

6: Frozen

7: Active, vacant

8: Additional (vacant/filled)

 

Posts occupied by personnel with temporary appointments, are labeled "Temporary".  All other posts are labeled "Permanent".  The total number of posts is the sum of the "Temporary" and "Permanent" posts.

 

The following Natures of Appointment do not occupy posts and are excluded from the data:

·          Periodical Remunerations

·          Abnormal Appointments.

 

Salary Band: The following Salary Levels will be linked to each Salary Band description as per report layout:

Lower skilled                                           =              Salary Levels 1 2

Skilled                                                      =              Salary Levels 3 5

Highly skilled production                          =              Salary Levels 6  8

Highly skilled supervision                        =              Salary Levels 9 12

Senior and Top Management                  =              Salary Levels 13  16

Other                                                       =              All Salary Levels not included above and everything higher

                                                                                 than Salary Level 16;

NOTE: In the report layout description where Salary Band is used, (Level 1  2), etc. refers to the Salary Level.

 

When a report layout refers to Senior Management Service Band A  D, the following Salary Levels will be applicable:

Senior Management Service Band A      =              Salary Level 13

Senior Management Service Band B      =              Salary Level 14

Senior Management Service Band C      =              Salary Level 15

Senior Management Service Band D      =              Salary Level 16.

B.        EXPENDITURE - TABLES 2.*

 

Description:

Departments budget in terms of clearly defined Programmes. The tables in this section summarise final audited expenditure by Programme (Table 2.1) and by Salary Bands (Table 2.2). In particular, it provides an indication of the amount spent on personnel costs in terms of each of the Programmes or Salary Bands within the department.

Definition:

Expenditure is the decrease in economic benefits during the accounting period in the form of outflows or depletion of assets or incurrence of liabilities that result in decreases in equity, other than those relating to distributions to equity participants.

Notes:

·          Note that the rounding on individual taxable allowances vs. calculation on the total taxable amount can cause differences in the calculation of the Regional Service Council expenditure;

·          The totals of Tables 2.3 and 2.4 should balance.

Description:

This table summarises final audited expenditure by Programme. In particular, it provides an indication of the amount spent on personnel costs in terms of each of the Programmes within the department.

Business Rules:

·          The table (detail in Columns A, B, C and D) only displays expenditure as extracted from the financial source systems; No information from PERSAL is shown;

·          Total Personnel Expenditure (H) is summarised per province-department by Salary Band/Programme/ SMS Band for record type 1 and 2, where record type 2 is a negative value;

·          If the departmental code file was not updated with the new Programme code at the time of extraction, then the code is displayed instead of a description;

·          For Gauteng province, all departments are posting to BAS on the new Standard Chart of Accounts. No mapping to standard items are currently available, therefore no expenditure is displayed for the Gauteng departments on BAS;

·          Programmes shown are as from the current financial source systems, i.e. BAS and FMS;

·          Employees in posts coupled to more than one objective are proportionally divided between the relevant Programmes;

·          Departments should add an additional column Employment (M) to capture the number of employees per Programme, as this information is not available on the financial source systems;

·          Calculations (refer Layout above):

Ø        Personnel Cost as % of Total Expenditure (E) = Personnel Expenditure (B) / Total Expenditure (A) * 100;

Ø        Average Personnel Cost per Employee (F) = Personnel Expenditure (B) / Employment (M);

Ø        Total of Personnel Cost as % of Total Expenditure (K) = Total of Personnel Expenditure (H) / Total of Total Expenditure (G) * 100;

Ø        Average Personnel Cost per Employee (L) = Total of Personnel Expenditure (H) / Total Employment (N).

Description:

The tables in this section summarise the position with regard to employment and vacancies.

Definition:

The tables summarise the number of posts on the establishment, the number of employees, the vacancy rate, and whether there are any staff that are additional to the establishment.

General Business Rules:

·          The following Post Status codes are included:

Ø        1:Active, filled

Ø        2:Lent

Ø        6:Frozen

Ø        7:Active, vacant

Ø        8:Additional, vacant/filled;

·          Posts occupied by employees with temporary appointments are labeled "Temporary". All other posts are labeled "Permanent";

·          The total number of posts is the sum of the "Temporary" and "Permanent" posts;

·          Refer Table 2.3 for detail on the Item codes used to classify salaries, overtime, home owners allowance and medical aid;

Ø        30: Education Specialist, temporary

·          Programmes, Occupational Classifications and Salary Levels reflect post information;

·          Posts coupled to more than one objective are proportionally divided between the relevant Programmes;

·          The following Natures of Appointment do not occupy posts and are excluded from the data:

Ø        Periodical remuneration

Ø        Abnormal appointments.

D.       JOB EVALUATION - TABLES 4.*

 

Description:

The Public Service Regulations, 1999 introduced job evaluation as a way of ensuring that work of equal value is remunerated equally. Within a nationally determined framework, executing authorities may evaluate or re-evaluate any job in his or her organisation. In terms of the PSR all vacancies on Salary Level 9 and higher must be evaluated before they are filled. This was complemented by a decision by the Minister for the Public Service and Administration that all SMS jobs must be evaluated before 31 December 2002.

General Business Rules:

·          The following Post Status codes are included:

Ø        1: Active, filled

Ø        2: Lent

Ø        6: Frozen

Ø        7: Active, vacant

Ø        8: Additional, vacant/filled;

·          The first appointment of an employee in a department is used as the headcount;

·          Due to the way in which the historical data was extracted from the PERSAL system, the following apply:

Ø        Occupants of session posts are excluded from the headcount;

·          The following Natures of Appointment do not occupy posts and are excluded from the data:

Ø        Periodical Remunerations

Ø        Abnormal Appointments.

(The number of employees might differ from the number of posts upgraded since not all employees are automatically absorbed into the new posts and some of the posts upgraded could also be vacant).

Business Rules:

·          All Key Scales that fit into a Salary Band are displayed per Salary Band. Totals per Salary Band are included;

·          All data is extracted from PERSAL  no exceptions on the data have been made during the extraction;

·          The procedure for posts on PERSAL to be upgraded or downgraded is as follows:

Ø        The department creates a new upgraded post and the employee is moved to that post. Reason for creation = upgrade;

Ø        The department abolishes an old post. Reason for abolishment = upgraded;

Ø        There currently is no relation between the old and new post;

Ø        % Downgraded Posts Evaluated (G) = Number of Posts Downgraded (F) / Number of Jobs Evaluated (B) * 100.

Notes:

PERSAL currently investigates the possibility to display the Salary Level on the post file for post information and the salary file for employee information.

I.         LEAVE UTILISATION FOR THE PERIOD 1 JANUARY 2003 TO 31 DECEMBER 2003 - TABLES 9.*

 

Description:

The Public Service Commission identified the need for careful monitoring of sick leave within the Public Service.  The tables in this section provide an indication of the use of sick- and disability leave. The estimated cost of the leave is also provided.

General Business Rules:

·          The dates on the leave reports are for the leave cycle and not per financial year;

·          Sick leave = category 04, 05, 07, 14, 51;

·          Disability  = category 52, 53;

·          Annual Leave = category 01 and 50;

·          In the calculation of the estimated cost, two different formulas are applied:

Ø        Work days = (Notch / 261) * Leave days;

Ø        Calendar days= (Notch / 365) * Leave days;

·          Leave payouts = 9650 and 9660;

·          Transfers between Main Frames:

Ø        The leave record for an employee is kept on the old bureau, as well as transferred to the new bureau;

Ø        An employees leave record is kept on the old bureau and is transferred to the new bureau;

Ø        Any backdated leave loaded on the old bureau after the transfer, is not transferred to the new bureau. Backdated leave can be loaded on both bureaus, which causes duplicate leave records.

Ø        Leave changes over time, e.g. if leave for May is extracted at the end of May and again at the end of December, the numbers will differ, as leave can either be captured immediately or long after the leave was taken.

3.        GLOSSARY & ACRONYMS

 

A.       GLOSSARY/BUSINESS DEFINITIONS

 

         i.            CORE Rank/Salary codes

CORE Rank/Salary codes are Rank/Salary codes, which have been converted to the CORE, i.e. Rank/Salary Codes ranging from 80000 to 89999.  

        ii.            Department of Public Service and Administration

The department of Public Service and Administration sets up all policies relating to any Human Resource issues, i.e. the CORE (Code of Remuneration) system, which is the new classification of ranks policy that replaced the old 'PAS' law. Also sets up salary level policies, leave rules and regulations, and any law relating to a government employee.                            

      iii.            Establishment

Establishment encompasses the PERSAL Service record and Posts structure. Approved Establishment means the posts that an executing authority has approved to carry out the core and support functions of the department.

      iv.            Estimate of National Expenditure

Through ongoing budget reforms and improved public expenditure management, Government seeks to enhance resource allocation in support of economic development and poverty alleviation.

Over the last few years we have made notable strides in aligning planning and budgeting within a medium-term framework, and have improved reporting on service delivery objectives and achievements. These improvements contribute to the effective delivery of essential services to our people, and to the achievement of Governments socio-economic goals.

 

The 2003 Estimates of National Expenditure provides a detailed account of the national

Governments service delivery commitments, and key policy developments over the medium term. These are described in the individual chapters of the thirty-four votes. The 2003 Estimates improves reporting on service delivery output targets, and also introduces brief summaries of recent achievements per programme.

 

For the first time, measurable objectives are introduced for each main division within a departments vote as prescribed by the Public Finance Management Act. Service delivery information is therefore complemented by an objective for each programme, which provides

Parliament and the public with a clear statement of the central aim of spending programmes. The introduction of these objectives raises the level of Governments commitment to budgetary transparency and accountability for expenditure outputs.

 

The Estimates of National Expenditure is intended to serve as a useful resource for the various committees of Parliament and contribute to public understanding and debate on public policy and expenditure plans. It is the outcome of a lengthy administrative and executive process through which political office-bearers and public officials collaborate to clarify policy priorities and spending plans over the medium term, as reflected in the range of tables in each chapter.

 

The ENE document has been produced by a dedicated team of National Treasury staff who worked closely with officials from all departments. For more information on this document, go to http://www.treasury.gov.za.

        v.            Major Occupational classification

Major Occupational Classification is the first and highest level of the Occupational Classification hierarchy.

      vi.            Minister of Public Service and Administration

The principal responsibility for overseeing, driving and coordinating the transformation process will rest with the Minister for the Public Service and Administration, on behalf of Cabinet and Parliament.

     vii.            Occupational Classification

Occupational Classification is a range of Rank/Salary Codes according to DPSA requirements, e.g. for Rank/Salary Code range 80119 to 80125, the Occupational Classification code is C1030400, for Rank/Salary Code range 80099 to 80104, the Occupational Classification code is G1010000, etc.

 

Only CORE Rank/Salary Codes are applicable.

   viii.            Programmes

A Programme represents a logical combination of related activities, elements and Sub-Programmes. Its function is to satisfy a departmental aim - the first level of an objective structure.

 

Programme Structure explains the general objectives for which funds are requested and contains Programmes established by the relevant department to attain those objectives. On the one hand the information is descriptive, while on the other details are provided in the money columns of the estimated expenditure to be incurred on various departmental Programmes, and their subdivisions, in achieving the relevant objective(s).

      ix.            Public Service Commission

Vision: The Public Service Commission is an independent and impartial body created by the constitution to enhance excellence in governance within the public service by promoting a professional and ethical environment and adding value to a public administration that is accountable, equitable, efficient, effective, corrupt-free and responsive to needs of the people of South Africa.

Mission: The Commission aims to promote the constitutionally enshrined democratic principles and values in the public service by investigating, monitoring, evaluating, communicating and reporting on the public administration; through research processes it will ensure the promoting of excellence in governance and the delivery of affordable and sustainable quality services.

The PSC is the independent monitor and arbiter of the activities, ethos and conduct of the Public Service. The powers and functions of the Commission are set out in Section 196 of the Constitution. The Commission is required to

1.        Promote the values and principles of public administration set out in Section 195 of the Constitution throughout the Public Service

2.        Monitor, evaluate and investigate human resource practices, service delivery and related organizational matters to assess the extent to which they comply with constitutional values and principles

3.        Support the efforts of the Public Service to promote a high standard of professional ethics

4.        Investigate grievances of officers and recommend appropriate remedies or actions

5.        Report to Parliament and provincial legislatures on its activities.

The PSC is one of a number of institutions whose role it is to support the legislature in enhancing accountability.

The Office of the Public Service Commission (OPSC) supports the PSC. It has established regional offices in each province, staffed by officials from the offices of former Provincial Service Commissions. A process of internal reorganization has been undertaken to ensure that the structure can support the PSC in delivering on its constitutional mandate.

Functions:

The Constitution, 1996, mandates the Commission to perform functions. In terms of Section 196(4) of the Constitution, the Commission shall:

(i) Promote the constitutionally prescribed values and principles governing public administration in the public service;

(ii) Investigate, monitor and evaluate the organisation and administration, and the personnel practices, of the public service;

(iii) Propose measures to ensure effective and efficient performance within the public service;

(iv) Give directions aimed at ensuring that personnel procedures relating to recruitment, transfers promotions and dismissals comply with the constitutionally prescribed values and principles;

(v) Report in respect of its activities and the performance of its functions, including any finding it may make and directions and advice it may give, and to provide an evaluation of the extent to which the constitutionally prescribed values and principles are complied with; and

(vi) Either of its own accord or on receipt of any complaint 

·          Investigate and evaluate the application of personnel and public administration practices, and report to the relevant executive authority and legislature;

·          Investigate grievances of employees in the public service concerning official acts or omissions, and recommend appropriate remedies;

·          Monitor and investigate adherence to applicable procedures in the public service; and

·          Advise national and provincial organs of state regarding personnel practices in the public service, including those relating to the recruitment, appointment, transfer, discharge and other aspects of the careers of employees in the public service.

In terms of item (v) above the Commission shall report at least once a year to the National Assembly; and, in respect of its activities in a province, to the legislature of the province.

The Commission will at all times retain its independent and impartial status. Such interaction will in no way affect its reporting to the National Assembly or the various Provincial Legislatures.

        x.            Public Service Co-ordinating Bargaining Council

The objectives of the Council, within its constitutional scope, shall be to-

(a) generally enhance labour peace in the public service;

(b) promote a sound relationship between the State as employer and its employees;

(c) in terms of the Act and this constitution, negotiate and bargain collectively to reach agreement on matters of mutual interest to the employer and employees represented by admitted trade unions in the Council;

(d) provide mechanisms for the resolution of disputes between the employer and (employees as well as) trade unions admitted to the Council, and to perform dispute resolution functions between the employer and employees within the registered scope of the Council, where the employer has the requisite authority to resolve such disputes;

(e) conclude, supervise and enforce collective agreements;

(f) comply with its duties and functions in terms of the Act and this constitution;

(g) and consider and deal with such other matters as may affect the interests of the parties to the Council.

 

For more information on the PSCBC, go to http://www.dpsa.gov.za/documents/pscbc/constitution.pdf.

     xii.            Salary Band

Grouping the different Salary Level - Notches values into 6 groups based on skill level, creates Salary Band - Notches. The first 3 numbers in the description of the Salary Band is the number of the Key Scale Table from which the Salary Level - Notch is read on PERSAL. Refer HR OVERSIGHT APPLICATION - GENERAL META DATA, General Business Rules.

   xiii.            Source System

PERSAL operational (transactional) source system.

   xiv.            Unit Occupational Classification

Unit Occupational Classification is the fourth level (refer Major Occupational Classification) of the Occupational Classification hierarchy.
